The Telegraph - Calcutta : Business

 Novel health cover for the poor

 OUR CORRESPONDENT

 New Delhi, Jan. 10: A low-cost, cashless health insurance scheme is now available for the poor at Rs 120 a year.

 In a unique partnership, private insurer ICICI Lombard, drug company Biocon India and Devi Shetty?s Narayana Hrudalaya have joined hands to sell Arogya Raksha.

 To start with, the insurance company is targeting to cover more than 6 lakh people residing in Anel Taluka district in Karnataka.

 The annual premium charged is Rs 180 for one or two members covered in a family, Rs 150 for three members and Rs 120 for more than four members insured in a family.

 The policy covers the policyholders against three days of hospitalisation for medical care and approximately 1,600 kinds of surgeries. It also entitles them to subsidised diagnostic tests and low-cost medicines. 




